text:
¬†@Bulldogg6404¬† I believe that background, while commonly accepted, may be incorrect.  This is about to turn into a small Japanese lesson, you can skip from this point on if you aren't here for that.


The "accepted translation" explanation doesn't make a lot of sense, but taking a dive into the language does prove to be rather fruitful.
"Tsuki" and "suki" sound very similar (and often prove to be the same when one is nervous) so it may simply be one of Japanese's many puns.  Even deeper, Japanese has a tendency to omit the subject(s) if they could be assumed based on context.
Combining these two factors, "tsukiga kireidesune" may have started as either a mispronunciation or mishearing of "sukiga kireidesune" or "isn't love beautiful"  which in turn may have been shortened from "sukinakoga kireidesune" or "the girl I like really is beautiful" with context indicating that the only other party there is the target of those affections.
Alternatively, it may have started as "sukika, kireidesune," meaning along the lines of "So you like me? That makes things clean" as a way of admitting that both parties share the same feelings.

As an aside, when you're reading an interview or a quote and they have portions of text in brackets [like this] they are filling in a blank based on context or adding to the sentence to complete it.  Take those quotations with a grain of salt as the one penning them may have assumed incorrectly.
